/* ============================================================
   Reasoning GP — Audio library scripts (3 of 5)
   CKS-style clinician summaries. Neurology · Mental health · Women's & sexual.
   ~5 min each: definition & lay explanation → risk factors → red flags →
   assessment → non-drug management → drug management → safety-netting →
   referral. Original summaries based on NICE CKS / NG guidance.
   ============================================================ */
window.RGP_AUDIO_TRACKS = (window.RGP_AUDIO_TRACKS || []).concat([

  /* ---------------- NEUROLOGY ---------------- */
  { id:'cks-headache', cat:'Neurology', ic:'🧠', dur:'5 min', title:'Headache & migraine', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for headache and migraine. The first task is to separate primary headaches — migraine, tension-type, and cluster — from secondary causes. In lay terms, reassure the patient that the great majority of headaches, including migraine, are not caused by anything dangerous such as a tumour, but are a real and treatable disorder of how the brain and its blood vessels and nerves behave. Risk factors and triggers for migraine include a family history, hormonal changes around periods, stress, poor or excess sleep, missed meals, dehydration, certain foods, and caffeine. Assessment: characterise the headache and screen for red flags. Migraine is typically a moderate-to-severe, often one-sided, pulsating headache lasting 4 to 72 hours, made worse by activity, with nausea and sensitivity to light and sound, sometimes preceded by an aura. Tension-type headache is bilateral, pressing or tight, and not disabling. Cluster headache is severe, one-sided around the eye, with tearing and a blocked nostril. Red flags suggesting serious secondary pathology must be screened for: thunderclap onset reaching maximum within minutes; headache worse on waking, coughing, or bending; a new headache over the age of 50; fever with neck stiffness; focal neurology or papilloedema; and a new headache in someone with cancer, HIV, or in pregnancy. Examine blood pressure, the fundi, and the neurology, and the temporal arteries in older people for giant cell arteritis. Investigations are not needed for typical primary headache; image or refer urgently for red flags. Non-drug management is important and should be emphasised: keep a headache diary to identify and address triggers, maintain regular sleep, meals, and hydration, manage stress, and reduce caffeine; explain and prevent medication-overuse headache by limiting acute painkillers. Drug management of migraine: for acute attacks, offer a triptan such as sumatriptan combined with an NSAID or paracetamol, plus an antiemetic, limiting acute treatment to no more than about ten days a month to avoid medication-overuse headache. For prevention, when attacks are frequent or disabling, offer propranolol, topiramate — which must be avoided in those who could become pregnant because of teratogenicity and reduced contraceptive efficacy — or amitriptyline, and consider acupuncture. For tension-type headache, offer simple analgesia and address contributors. Safety-netting and referral: counsel on safe analgesic use, advise which symptoms require urgent review, refer cluster headache for specialist treatment, and refer for diagnostic uncertainty, refractory migraine, or any red flags.' },

  { id:'cks-stroke-tia', cat:'Neurology', ic:'🧠', dur:'5 min', title:'Stroke & TIA', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for stroke and transient ischaemic attack. Definition: a stroke is an acute focal neurological deficit from a vascular cause, either ischaemic from a blocked artery or haemorrhagic from a bleed; a TIA is a transient episode of focal neurological dysfunction without lasting infarction, with symptoms typically resolving within an hour. In lay terms, explain that a stroke is a "brain attack" where part of the brain loses its blood supply, that it is an emergency because rapid treatment saves brain tissue, and that a TIA is a warning sign that must be acted on to prevent a full stroke. Risk factors include hypertension — the biggest — atrial fibrillation, diabetes, high cholesterol, smoking, obesity, excess alcohol, and increasing age. Assessment: suspect stroke with sudden focal symptoms — facial weakness, arm or leg weakness, speech disturbance, visual loss, or acute vertigo with other signs — using the FAST test: face, arms, speech, time. Red flags and urgency: a suspected acute stroke is a 999 emergency — arrange immediate transfer for brain imaging and consideration of thrombolysis and thrombectomy, as treatment is strictly time-critical, and do not delay for other investigations. Examine for focal neurology, blood pressure, heart rhythm for atrial fibrillation, and carotid bruits. Management of a suspected TIA: give aspirin 300 milligrams immediately unless contraindicated, and refer for specialist assessment within 24 hours; do not use risk scores to delay specialist review. Secondary prevention after a confirmed ischaemic event, once haemorrhage is excluded, includes long-term antiplatelet therapy such as clopidogrel, or anticoagulation for atrial fibrillation, a high-intensity statin, blood-pressure control, and management of all vascular risk factors. Arrange carotid imaging, as significant symptomatic carotid stenosis may need endarterectomy. Non-drug management is central to prevention: support smoking cessation, a healthy diet, physical activity, weight loss, and reducing alcohol. Safety-netting and referral: advise on driving — the person must not drive for at least a month and there are DVLA rules — reinforce that recurrent symptoms are an emergency, support rehabilitation and address mood, communication, and function after stroke, and refer to stroke services.' },

  { id:'cks-epilepsy', cat:'Neurology', ic:'⚡', dur:'5 min', title:'Epilepsy & first seizure', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for epilepsy and the first seizure. Definition: epilepsy is a tendency to recurrent unprovoked seizures caused by abnormal electrical activity in the brain. In lay terms, explain that a seizure is a burst of disordered electrical activity in the brain, that a single seizure does not necessarily mean epilepsy, and that once diagnosed it is usually well controlled with medication so that most people lead full lives. Risk factors include a family history, previous brain injury, stroke, infection, or structural brain abnormality, and provoking factors such as sleep deprivation, alcohol, and some drugs. Assessment: a detailed eyewitness account is the single most valuable diagnostic tool — ask about any warning or aura, the nature and progression of any movements, tongue-biting and incontinence, the duration, and the recovery with post-ictal confusion. Distinguish epileptic seizures from syncope, which has situational triggers, pallor, and rapid recovery, and from other causes of transient loss of consciousness. After a first suspected seizure, do an ECG to exclude a cardiac cause and bloods including glucose and electrolytes, and refer to a first-fit clinic to be seen within two weeks for EEG and brain MRI. Red flags and safety: recognise status epilepticus — a seizure lasting more than five minutes or repeated seizures without recovery — as a medical emergency. Give immediate safety advice after any seizure: the person must not drive and must inform the DVLA, and counsel on water safety, heights, and dangerous machinery, and on seizure first aid for the family. Management: do not start antiepileptic drugs in primary care; treatment is initiated by specialists once the diagnosis and seizure type are established, choosing the drug by seizure type and the person\u2019s circumstances. The primary-care role includes supporting adherence, awareness of drug interactions and side effects, the annual review, and crucially counselling on pregnancy and contraception — sodium valproate is highly teratogenic and is contraindicated in those able to become pregnant except under strict specialist conditions. Non-drug management includes identifying and avoiding triggers such as sleep deprivation and excess alcohol, and supporting self-management. Safety-netting and referral: refer for poor seizure control, pregnancy planning, a change in seizure pattern, or any diagnostic uncertainty, and ensure the person knows when a seizure becomes an emergency.' },

  { id:'cks-parkinsons', cat:'Neurology', ic:'🧠', dur:'5 min', title:'Parkinson\u2019s disease', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for Parkinson\u2019s disease. Definition: a progressive neurodegenerative disorder caused by loss of dopamine-producing neurons, characterised by the motor features remembered as TRAP — tremor, rigidity, akinesia or bradykinesia, and postural instability. In lay terms, explain that the brain is gradually losing cells that produce dopamine, a chemical that helps control movement, that the symptoms come on slowly and can be helped considerably by medication, and that a specialist guides treatment. Risk factors include increasing age, male sex, and a family history, with most cases being sporadic. Assessment: suspect Parkinson\u2019s from an asymmetrical resting, pill-rolling tremor, bradykinesia with reducing amplitude on repetitive movements, and rigidity. Ask about non-motor features that often predate the diagnosis — reduced sense of smell, constipation, REM sleep behaviour disorder, low mood, and later cognitive change. Examine for the resting tremor, cogwheel rigidity, bradykinesia, a stooped shuffling gait with reduced arm swing, and a mask-like face; Parkinson\u2019s is a clinical diagnosis, and specialists may use a DaTscan to clarify it. Red flags and safety principles: two safety messages matter in any setting — first, Parkinson\u2019s medications must be given on time, because missed or delayed doses cause severe immobility and can be dangerous, so honour the "Get It On Time" approach in hospital and at home; second, never use metoclopramide or prochlorperazine for nausea as they block dopamine and worsen Parkinson\u2019s — domperidone is preferred. Management: refer people with suspected Parkinson\u2019s, untreated, to a specialist before starting treatment, ideally seen within six weeks, and do not start antiparkinsonian medication in primary care. Specialist treatment is usually levodopa for those whose motor symptoms affect quality of life, with dopamine agonists, MAO-B inhibitors, and others as alternatives or adjuncts. Non-drug management is important: physiotherapy for movement and balance, occupational therapy, speech and language therapy for speech and swallowing, exercise, and falls prevention. Safety-netting and referral: the primary-care role includes recognising the diagnosis, supporting between specialist reviews, anticipating motor and non-motor complications including mood and psychosis, addressing falls and the carer\u2019s needs, and discussing advance care planning as the disease progresses.' },

  { id:'cks-bells', cat:'Neurology', ic:'😐', dur:'5 min', title:'Bell\u2019s palsy', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for Bell\u2019s palsy. Definition: an acute, idiopathic, lower motor neurone facial nerve palsy — a diagnosis of exclusion. In lay terms, reassure the patient that this is a weakness of the nerve that moves one side of the face, that it is not a stroke, and that most people recover well over weeks to months, especially with prompt treatment. Risk factors include pregnancy and diabetes, and it can follow a viral illness. Assessment: ask about the rapid onset, over hours to a couple of days, of one-sided facial weakness, sometimes with pain behind the ear, altered taste, and increased sensitivity to sound. The crucial clinical step is to determine whether the forehead is involved: in Bell\u2019s palsy, a lower motor neurone lesion, the weakness affects the whole side of the face including the forehead, so the person cannot raise the eyebrow or fully close the eye. Red flag: forehead sparing indicates an upper motor neurone lesion such as a stroke, which needs urgent assessment. Examine the face, look in the ear for the vesicles of Ramsay Hunt syndrome from shingles of the facial nerve, check eye closure and the cornea, and exclude other causes such as a parotid mass or other cranial-nerve signs. Investigations are usually not needed; the diagnosis is clinical once other causes are excluded. Drug management: offer oral prednisolone, ideally started within 72 hours of onset, which improves the likelihood of complete recovery; the evidence does not support routinely adding an antiviral for Bell\u2019s palsy, though some specialists do in severe cases, and Ramsay Hunt syndrome does need an antiviral with the steroid. Non-drug management — eye protection — is critical, because incomplete eye closure risks corneal damage: advise lubricating drops during the day, ointment and taping the eye closed at night, and seeking help for eye pain or redness. Safety-netting and referral: reassure that most people recover well, but refer urgently if a stroke is possible (forehead sparing) or for suspected Ramsay Hunt syndrome; refer for no improvement by three weeks, atypical, bilateral, or recurrent features, worsening weakness, or any eye complication, and review recovery.' },

  { id:'cks-vertigo', cat:'Neurology', ic:'🌀', dur:'5 min', title:'Dizziness & vertigo', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for dizziness and vertigo. The first step is to clarify what the person means — true vertigo is an illusion of movement, usually spinning, distinct from light-headedness, faintness, or unsteadiness, which have different causes. In lay terms, explain that vertigo usually comes from the balance organs in the inner ear, that it is unpleasant but most causes are not serious and settle, and that simple treatments often help quickly. Assessment: for vertigo, the timing and triggers point to the cause. Brief vertigo provoked by head movement or rolling over suggests benign paroxysmal positional vertigo, or BPPV. A single prolonged episode lasting days with nausea, often after a viral illness, suggests vestibular neuritis, or labyrinthitis if there is also hearing loss. Recurrent spontaneous episodes with hearing loss, tinnitus, and a sense of fullness in the ear suggest Meniere\u2019s disease. Red flags: crucially, screen for central causes — accompanying neurological symptoms, a new headache, an inability to walk unaided, sudden deafness, or vascular risk factors raising concern for a posterior-circulation stroke. Examine for the type and direction of nystagmus, perform the Dix-Hallpike test for BPPV, examine the ears, cranial nerves, and gait, and consider the HINTS examination in acute persistent vertigo to help distinguish peripheral from central causes. Non-drug management is often the most effective: treat BPPV with the Epley repositioning manoeuvre, which is highly effective, and teach home exercises; for vestibular neuritis, encourage early movement and vestibular rehabilitation exercises to promote central compensation. Drug management: for vestibular neuritis, a short course of a vestibular sedative such as prochlorperazine for a few days can ease severe symptoms, but stop it early because prolonged use delays recovery. For Meniere\u2019s disease, consider betahistine and dietary salt reduction. Treat any underlying cause. Safety-netting and referral: refer urgently if central or stroke features are present; refer to ENT or neurology for diagnostic uncertainty, persistent or recurrent vertigo, or hearing loss, and to ENT for suspected Meniere\u2019s disease. Reassure where the cause is peripheral and benign and arrange follow-up for symptom control and rehabilitation.' },

  { id:'cks-neuropathy', cat:'Neurology', ic:'🦵', dur:'5 min', title:'Peripheral neuropathy', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for peripheral neuropathy. Definition: dysfunction of the peripheral nerves, most commonly a length-dependent sensory polyneuropathy producing a glove-and-stocking pattern of symptoms. In lay terms, explain that the small nerves supplying the feet and hands are not working properly, often because of an underlying condition such as diabetes, and that treatment aims both to tackle that cause and to ease the nerve pain. Risk factors and causes: diabetes is the commonest cause, along with excess alcohol, vitamin B12 deficiency, hypothyroidism, chronic kidney disease, certain drugs including some chemotherapy, and inherited causes. Assessment: ask about numbness, tingling, burning pain, and weakness, typically starting in the feet and progressing upwards. Examine to map the sensory loss, test vibration and proprioception, check reflexes — often reduced or absent at the ankles — and assess for weakness and wasting; look for a foot deformity such as a high arch suggesting a hereditary cause. Red flag: rapidly progressive or ascending weakness with loss of reflexes raises concern for Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome, which is a medical emergency needing immediate admission. Investigate to find the cause: HbA1c or fasting glucose, B12 and folate, thyroid function, renal and liver function, a full blood count, and consider an autoimmune and paraprotein screen; nerve conduction studies are arranged through neurology. Management: treat the underlying cause — optimise glycaemic control, replace B12, reduce alcohol, correct hypothyroidism, and review culprit drugs — as this can halt or improve the neuropathy. Non-drug management includes structured foot-care advice given the loss of protective sensation, particularly in diabetes, to prevent ulceration, plus advice on alcohol and lifestyle. Drug management of neuropathic pain: NICE recommends offering a choice of amitriptyline, duloxetine, gabapentin, or pregabalin, switching to another if the first is not effective or tolerated, with tramadol only as rescue and capsaicin cream for localised pain. Safety-netting and referral: refer to neurology for an unclear cause, atypical or asymmetrical features, motor-predominant or rapidly progressive neuropathy, and refer urgently for suspected Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome; review symptom control and the underlying condition over time.' },

  /* ---------------- MENTAL HEALTH ---------------- */
  { id:'cks-depression', cat:'Mental health', ic:'🌧️', dur:'5 min', title:'Depression', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for depression in adults, following NICE guideline NG222. In lay terms, explain that depression is a common and treatable illness, not a weakness or something to "snap out of", that it affects mood, energy, sleep, and thinking, and that talking therapies, lifestyle change, and where needed medication all help. Risk factors include a previous episode or family history, chronic physical illness or pain, recent loss or stress, social isolation, substance misuse, and the postnatal period. Assessment: ask about the core symptoms — persistent low mood and loss of interest or pleasure — present most days for at least two weeks, with associated symptoms including sleep and appetite change, fatigue, poor concentration, feelings of worthlessness or guilt, and hopelessness. Red flags and risk: always assess risk — thoughts of self-harm or suicide, any intent and plans, protective factors, and risk to dependents — and ask about any history of mania or hypomania to detect bipolar disorder, which changes management. Screen with a validated tool such as the PHQ-9 to grade severity and monitor response, and consider organic contributors such as hypothyroidism. Categorise as less severe — subthreshold and mild — or more severe — moderate and severe. Non-drug management is first-line for many: for less severe depression, do not routinely offer antidepressants first unless preferred; offer options such as guided self-help, group cognitive behavioural therapy, group exercise, mindfulness, or other psychological therapies, and give advice on sleep, activity, and social connection. Drug management: for more severe depression, offer a combination of an individual psychological therapy and an antidepressant, or either alone by preference; an SSRI such as sertraline is a usual first-line choice. Counsel on the delayed onset of benefit over a few weeks, the side effects, and that stopping should be gradual to avoid discontinuation symptoms. Safety-netting is essential: review within one to two weeks of starting, and within one week for people under 30 or at higher risk, because of the early risk of increased suicidal thoughts, and give clear crisis advice. Referral: refer to specialist mental-health services for severe, complex, treatment-resistant, or high-risk presentations, psychotic depression, or suspected bipolar disorder, and support self-management with structured follow-up.' },

  { id:'cks-gad', cat:'Mental health', ic:'🌀', dur:'5 min', title:'Generalised anxiety disorder', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for generalised anxiety disorder, following NICE guideline CG113. In lay terms, explain that anxiety is the body\u2019s alarm system becoming overactive, producing excessive worry and physical symptoms even when there is no real danger, and that it is common, understandable, and treatable with talking therapies and, if needed, medication. Risk factors include a family history, childhood adversity, chronic stress, other mental-health conditions, and substance use. Assessment: ask about excessive, difficult-to-control worry across multiple areas of life, on most days for at least six months, with symptoms such as restlessness, fatigue, poor concentration, irritability, muscle tension, and disturbed sleep. Distinguish it from panic disorder, phobias, and anxiety secondary to depression, substance use, or a physical cause. Red flags and assessment points: screen for depression and suicidal ideation, which commonly coexist, and consider a physical cause such as hyperthyroidism — check thyroid function and other tests if suspected. Use the GAD-7 to measure severity and monitor. Management follows the stepped-care model. Step 1 is identification, education about the disorder, and active monitoring, as many improve. Step 2, for those who do not improve, offers low-intensity psychological interventions such as guided self-help based on cognitive behavioural therapy or psychoeducational groups. Step 3, for marked functional impairment or inadequate response, offers a choice of a high-intensity psychological therapy such as CBT, or drug treatment. Non-drug management threads throughout: explain the condition, encourage exercise, good sleep, reduced caffeine and alcohol, and self-help resources. Drug management: first-line is an SSRI such as sertraline; if ineffective or not tolerated, offer an alternative SSRI or an SNRI such as venlafaxine or duloxetine. Crucially, do not offer a benzodiazepine except as a short-term measure in a crisis, because of dependence. Counsel on the delayed onset and side effects of antidepressants. Safety-netting and referral: review within two to four weeks of starting, and sooner in those under 30; step 4 is referral to specialist services for severe, complex, treatment-resistant, or high-risk disorder, and address comorbid depression and substance use.' },

  { id:'cks-bipolar', cat:'Mental health', ic:'🎭', dur:'5 min', title:'Bipolar disorder', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for bipolar disorder. Definition: a recurrent mood disorder with episodes of mania or hypomania and usually episodes of depression. In lay terms, explain that bipolar disorder involves the mood swinging between extreme highs, where a person may feel elated, overactive, and need little sleep, and lows of depression, and that it is a long-term but manageable condition with specialist-guided treatment. Risk factors include a strong family history, and onset is typically in late adolescence or early adulthood. Assessment: recognising mania or hypomania is the key — elevated or irritable mood with increased energy and activity, a reduced need for sleep, rapid speech, grandiosity, distractibility, and risky or disinhibited behaviour. A common and important pitfall is treating apparent unipolar depression while missing a past manic or hypomanic episode, so when assessing any depression always ask about previous periods of elevated mood and overactivity. Red flags and risk: assess risk carefully in both phases — risk to self and others, and from disinhibited behaviour and impaired judgement — and ask about substance use; acute mania, or severe depression with risk, needs urgent or emergency mental-health assessment, potentially under the Mental Health Act. Investigate to exclude organic and substance causes — thyroid function and a drug screen — and obtain baseline bloods before mood stabilisers. Management: refer people with suspected bipolar disorder to specialist mental-health services for diagnosis; do not diagnose it in primary care. Long-term treatment is specialist-led, using mood stabilisers such as lithium, or certain antipsychotics, to prevent relapse; antidepressants can precipitate mania and are used cautiously, usually only alongside a mood stabiliser. Non-drug management includes psychoeducation, recognising early relapse signs, regular routine and sleep, and reducing alcohol and drugs. The primary-care role is largely shared-care: monitoring lithium levels with renal, thyroid, and calcium checks, attending to the markedly raised physical-health and cardiovascular risk, and supporting adherence. Safety-netting and referral: counsel on pregnancy and contraception as several drugs including valproate are teratogenic, refer relapses, and review wellbeing, monitoring, and physical health regularly.' },

  { id:'cks-insomnia', cat:'Mental health', ic:'🌙', dur:'5 min', title:'Insomnia', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for insomnia. Definition: difficulty getting to sleep, staying asleep, or poor-quality sleep despite adequate opportunity, with daytime consequences; it is short-term if under three months and long-term if longer. In lay terms, reassure the patient that occasional poor sleep is normal, that the body is resilient to it, and that the most effective long-term treatment is changing sleep habits and unhelpful thoughts about sleep rather than sleeping tablets, which have only a limited short-term role. Risk factors include stress, anxiety and depression, chronic pain, caffeine, alcohol, nicotine, shift work, screen use at night, and an irregular routine. Assessment: clarify the pattern — difficulty initiating sleep, frequent waking, or early-morning waking — and the daytime impact. Ask about sleep habits, the bedroom environment, and stimulants. Crucially, screen for and identify underlying causes — depression, anxiety, chronic pain, restless legs syndrome, and obstructive sleep apnoea suggested by snoring and daytime sleepiness — and review medications and substances. A sleep diary over one to two weeks is the most useful assessment tool. Investigate guided by suspected causes, for example thyroid function, or refer for assessment of sleep apnoea. Non-drug management is first-line and should be emphasised: give sleep-hygiene advice — a regular routine, a comfortable dark bedroom, avoiding caffeine, alcohol, and screens before bed, and getting up if not asleep — and, most importantly, offer cognitive behavioural therapy for insomnia, which is the most effective long-term treatment and is recommended ahead of medication, including digital programmes. Drug management: reserve hypnotics such as a short-acting Z-drug or short-acting benzodiazepine for short-term use only in severe, disabling insomnia, at the lowest effective dose for the shortest time, ideally no more than two weeks, because of tolerance, dependence, and next-day impairment; avoid long-term hypnotics and support withdrawal in those already dependent. Safety-netting and referral: counsel about driving and the risks of sedatives, refer for suspected sleep apnoea or other primary sleep disorders, and review and reinforce the non-drug strategies for persistent insomnia.' },

  { id:'cks-alcohol', cat:'Mental health', ic:'🍺', dur:'5 min', title:'Alcohol-use disorders', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for alcohol-use disorders. In lay terms, approach the subject without judgement, explain the recommended low-risk limit of no more than 14 units a week spread over several days, and frame cutting down or stopping as something achievable with support that brings real health benefits. Risk factors and harms span physical — liver disease, hypertension, several cancers, and injury — mental health, and social consequences. Assessment: ask non-judgementally about the quantity and pattern of drinking in units, and screen with a validated tool such as AUDIT, or the shorter AUDIT-C, to identify increasing-risk, higher-risk, and possibly dependent drinking. Assess for features of dependence — craving, tolerance, difficulty controlling intake, and withdrawal symptoms such as morning shakes, sweating, and anxiety relieved by drinking. Assess the impact on physical and mental health, relationships, and work, and screen for depression, anxiety, and other substance use. Examine for signs of liver disease, and investigate with liver function tests including GGT, a full blood count for a raised mean cell volume, and a fibrosis assessment such as FIB-4 to evaluate the risk of liver scarring. Red flags and a crucial safety point: do not advise abrupt cessation in someone who is alcohol-dependent without support, because withdrawal can cause seizures and delirium tremens — assisted withdrawal uses a tapering benzodiazepine regimen, with thiamine to prevent Wernicke\u2019s encephalopathy, giving parenteral thiamine where there is risk. Management: for increasing- and higher-risk drinking without dependence, offer a brief intervention with structured advice and feedback, which is effective. For moderate and severe dependence, refer to specialist alcohol services. After successful withdrawal, relapse-prevention medication such as acamprosate or naltrexone, alongside psychological support, helps maintain abstinence. Non-drug management includes psychological support, addressing coexisting mental-health problems and social needs, and supporting the family. Safety-netting and referral: refer for severe dependence, complex needs, decompensated liver disease, or failed community treatment, and admit for high-risk withdrawal or suspected Wernicke\u2019s encephalopathy, which is a medical emergency.' },

  { id:'cks-dementia', cat:'Mental health', ic:'🧠', dur:'5 min', title:'Dementia', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for dementia. Definition: an acquired, progressive decline in cognition that affects daily function, with subtypes including Alzheimer\u2019s disease, vascular dementia, dementia with Lewy bodies, and frontotemporal dementia. In lay terms, explain sensitively that dementia is a condition where the brain\u2019s abilities — memory, thinking, and managing daily life — decline over time, that a diagnosis allows access to treatment, support, and planning, and that much can be done to help the person and their family live well. Risk factors include increasing age, family history, cardiovascular risk factors especially for vascular dementia, and Down syndrome. Assessment: take a history, ideally with a collateral account from a relative, of progressive decline in memory and other cognitive domains over months to years, and the functional impact. Note the pattern — gradual memory decline in Alzheimer\u2019s, stepwise in vascular dementia, fluctuating cognition with visual hallucinations and parkinsonism in Lewy body dementia, and early personality and behaviour change in frontotemporal dementia. Red flags and key exclusions: crucially, exclude delirium, which is acute, fluctuating, and often reversible, and depression, which can mimic dementia as "pseudodementia". Use a validated cognitive tool such as the 6-CIT or MoCA, examine for focal neurology and cardiovascular disease, and assess mood. Investigate to exclude reversible contributors with bloods — full blood count, renal and liver function, calcium, glucose or HbA1c, thyroid function, and B12 and folate. Management: refer to a memory assessment service for diagnosis and subtyping. Specialists may start an acetylcholinesterase inhibitor such as donepezil for Alzheimer\u2019s disease, or memantine; avoid antipsychotics for behavioural symptoms unless there is severe distress or risk, especially in Lewy body dementia where they can cause severe reactions. Non-drug management is central: structured support, cognitive stimulation, managing behavioural and psychological symptoms with non-drug approaches first, and supporting carers. Safety-netting and referral: coordinate care, manage cardiovascular risk in vascular dementia, address advance care planning, lasting power of attorney, and the duty to advise about driving and informing the DVLA, support carers and signpost to help, and review regularly including the carer\u2019s needs.' },

  { id:'cks-adhd', cat:'Mental health', ic:'🎯', dur:'5 min', title:'Adult ADHD', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for attention deficit hyperactivity disorder in adults. Definition: a neurodevelopmental disorder of persistent inattention and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity that began in childhood and continues to cause impairment. In lay terms, explain that ADHD reflects differences in how the brain regulates attention and impulses, that it is not a result of laziness or poor effort, and that diagnosis and treatment — which may include strategies, support, and medication — can substantially improve daily life. Risk factors include a family history, and it commonly coexists with anxiety, depression, and substance misuse. Assessment: ask about long-standing, since-childhood difficulties — inattention such as distractibility, disorganisation, forgetfulness, and not finishing tasks, and hyperactivity-impulsivity such as restlessness, interrupting, and acting without thinking. Symptoms must cause significant impairment in more than one setting, such as work and home, and not be better explained by another condition. Ask about the impact and about coexisting conditions. The assessment uses a structured history, rating scales, and, where possible, collateral and developmental information; there is no diagnostic blood test. Baseline observations including blood pressure, pulse, and weight, and sometimes an ECG, are needed before medication. Red flags and safety: assess mood and risk, and screen for substance misuse, which affects management and the safety of stimulant treatment. Management: refer to a specialist ADHD service for diagnosis, as ADHD should not be diagnosed in primary care. Treatment combines psychoeducation, environmental and behavioural strategies, and, where indicated, medication — stimulants such as methylphenidate or lisdexamfetamine, or non-stimulants such as atomoxetine — all initiated and titrated by specialists. Non-drug management includes practical strategies for organisation and time management, support, and reasonable adjustments at work or study. The primary-care role is largely through shared-care agreements: continuing prescriptions and monitoring height, weight, blood pressure, and heart rate, watching for side effects, and supporting adherence. Safety-netting and referral: treat coexisting anxiety and depression, refer back for poor response, significant side effects, or changing needs, and review regularly.' },

  /* ---------------- WOMEN'S & SEXUAL HEALTH ---------------- */
  { id:'cks-menopause', cat:"Women's & sexual health", ic:'🌡️', dur:'5 min', title:'Menopause & HRT', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for the menopause, following NICE guideline NG23. Definition: the permanent cessation of menstruation from loss of ovarian function, with the perimenopause being the transition around it. In lay terms, explain that the ovaries are gradually producing less oestrogen, which causes the symptoms, that this is a natural life stage but the symptoms can be troublesome, and that effective treatments — including hormone replacement therapy — are available and for most women safe. Risk factors for an earlier or more symptomatic menopause include smoking and surgical or medical ovarian failure; premature ovarian insufficiency occurs before the age of 40. Assessment: ask about vasomotor symptoms such as hot flushes and night sweats, mood and sleep disturbance, cognitive symptoms, joint aches, and genitourinary symptoms including vaginal dryness and urinary problems, and note the menstrual pattern. A key diagnostic point: in women over 45 with typical symptoms, diagnose the menopause and perimenopause clinically without blood tests. An FSH test has a limited role — mainly in women under 45 with suspected premature ovarian insufficiency, or where the picture is unclear — and is unreliable in women on hormonal contraception. Check blood pressure and BMI before HRT. Red flags: investigate any unscheduled or postmenopausal bleeding separately, as it can indicate endometrial pathology. Non-drug management: offer information and lifestyle measures, and discuss non-hormonal options such as cognitive behavioural therapy for low mood and flushes where HRT is unsuitable or not wanted. Drug management: HRT is the most effective treatment for vasomotor symptoms and is first-line for most women, where the benefits usually outweigh the risks. For a woman with a uterus, give combined oestrogen and progestogen to protect the womb lining; for a woman without a uterus, oestrogen alone. Transdermal oestrogen — patch or gel — avoids the small additional clot risk of oral oestrogen and is preferred in those with cardiovascular or clot risk factors. Discuss the small, duration-related increase in breast-cancer risk with combined HRT. Offer vaginal oestrogen for genitourinary symptoms, which is safe and can be used long-term, including alongside systemic HRT. Safety-netting and referral: review at three months after starting or changing, then at least annually, and refer for diagnostic uncertainty, premature ovarian insufficiency, or treatment-resistant symptoms.' },

  { id:'cks-hmb', cat:"Women's & sexual health", ic:'🩸', dur:'5 min', title:'Heavy menstrual bleeding', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for heavy menstrual bleeding, following NICE guideline NG88. Definition: excessive menstrual blood loss that interferes with quality of life — defined by its impact rather than a measured volume. In lay terms, validate that heavy periods are a genuine problem affecting daily life, that they are common and very treatable, and that an effective first-choice treatment, the hormonal coil, also acts as contraception. Causes and risk factors include fibroids, adenomyosis, polyps, a bleeding disorder, thyroid disease, and the hormonal coil being a treatment rather than a cause. Assessment: ask about the volume and impact — flooding, large clots, frequently changing protection, and the effect on daily life — and about intermenstrual, postcoital, or persistent bleeding, which need separate assessment. Ask about anaemia symptoms, features suggesting fibroids or adenomyosis, and a bleeding tendency since menarche. Examine the abdomen and, where indicated by symptoms or before some treatments, perform a pelvic and speculum examination. Check a full blood count in all women with heavy menstrual bleeding to detect iron-deficiency anaemia. Red flags and investigation: arrange a pelvic ultrasound if the uterus is enlarged or palpable, there are pelvic symptoms or a suspected mass, or treatment fails; and consider endometrial sampling for risk factors for endometrial cancer — for example persistent intermenstrual bleeding, or women 45 and over with treatment failure. Drug and device management: where there is no structural or histological cause, or fibroids under 3 centimetres, first-line if contraception is acceptable is the levonorgestrel intrauterine system, the most effective medical treatment; alternatives include tranexamic acid taken during menstruation to reduce loss, or an NSAID such as mefenamic acid which also helps period pain, and the combined oral contraceptive pill or cyclical progestogens. Treat iron-deficiency anaemia. Non-drug and supportive measures include addressing the impact and discussing options in line with the woman\u2019s preferences and contraceptive needs. Safety-netting and referral: refer to gynaecology for large or symptomatic fibroids, suspected pathology, treatment failure, or where surgical options such as endometrial ablation or myomectomy are being considered, and review the response and adjust treatment.' },

  { id:'cks-contraception', cat:"Women's & sexual health", ic:'💊', dur:'5 min', title:'Contraception', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for contraception. In lay terms, support the person to choose a method that fits their life, explaining the trade-offs between effectiveness, how often they need to think about it, the bleeding pattern, and any added benefits, and reassuring that methods can be changed. Assessment: explore what the person wants — effectiveness, reversibility, bleeding pattern, and non-contraceptive benefits — and take a medical history to apply the UK Medical Eligibility Criteria, the UKMEC, which classify how safe each method is for a given condition. Red flags and key safety examples: combined hormonal contraception is contraindicated, UKMEC 4, in migraine with aura, and is cautioned with hypertension, smoking at 35 or over, obesity, and other vascular risk factors, because of venous and arterial thrombosis risk; measure blood pressure and BMI before starting combined methods. Offer STI screening where relevant. Management: discuss long-acting reversible contraception first, because LARC methods — the progestogen implant, the levonorgestrel intrauterine system, the copper intrauterine device, and the injectable — are the most effective, as they do not depend on daily adherence, and are highly cost-effective. The copper coil is also the most effective emergency contraception. The progestogen-only pill is suitable for those who cannot use oestrogen and must be taken consistently. Non-drug and counselling elements are central: counsel on correct use, what to do about missed pills, the bleeding patterns to expect, the return of fertility after stopping, and safer-sex and STI protection. Provide emergency contraception promptly when needed — a copper IUD is most effective, or oral ulipristal acetate or levonorgestrel within their time windows — and arrange ongoing contraception. Safety-netting and referral: follow the UKMEC for safety, review blood pressure for combined methods, refer or signpost for intrauterine and subdermal fitting if not provided locally, and seek specialist input for complex medical eligibility decisions.' },

  { id:'cks-pcos', cat:"Women's & sexual health", ic:'🔬', dur:'5 min', title:'Polycystic ovary syndrome', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for polycystic ovary syndrome, or PCOS. Definition: a common hormonal disorder strongly associated with insulin resistance, defined by the Rotterdam criteria. In lay terms, explain that PCOS is a common condition affecting how the ovaries work and how the body handles insulin, that it can cause irregular periods, excess hair, acne, and weight gain, and that it also has longer-term health implications which can be managed. Risk factors include a family history and obesity, though it occurs in lean women too. Assessment: ask about irregular or absent periods, symptoms of excess androgens such as hirsutism and acne, difficulty conceiving, and weight gain. Examine for hirsutism, acne, acanthosis nigricans, and measure BMI and blood pressure. Diagnose using the Rotterdam criteria — at least two of three: infrequent or absent ovulation, clinical or biochemical hyperandrogenism, and polycystic ovaries on ultrasound — after excluding other causes of the symptoms. Investigate with total testosterone and sex hormone binding globulin, LH and FSH, prolactin, and thyroid function to exclude mimics, and consider 17-hydroxyprogesterone if congenital adrenal hyperplasia is possible. Screen metabolic risk with HbA1c or a glucose tolerance test and a lipid profile, and arrange a pelvic ultrasound. Red flags: infrequent periods increase the long-term risk of endometrial cancer, so ensure regular endometrial shedding, and prolonged amenorrhoea warrants attention. Non-drug management is foundational: weight management through diet and physical activity is central and improves all features — menstrual regularity, fertility, and metabolic risk. Drug management is tailored: for menstrual regulation and endometrial protection offer the combined oral contraceptive pill or cyclical progestogens, ensuring a withdrawal bleed at least every three to four months; for hirsutism offer cosmetic measures and the combined pill; for fertility refer for ovulation induction, for example with letrozole or clomifene, after optimising weight. Safety-netting and referral: address the long-term metabolic risks — monitor for type 2 diabetes, manage cardiovascular risk factors, and consider sleep apnoea and mood — refer for fertility treatment, diagnostic uncertainty, or refractory hyperandrogenism, and review weight, metabolic risk, and menstrual pattern.' },

  { id:'cks-ovarian-ca', cat:"Women's & sexual health", ic:'🎗️', dur:'5 min', title:'Suspected ovarian cancer', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for suspected ovarian cancer, following NICE NG12 and the ovarian cancer guidance. The central challenge is that symptoms are vague and easily attributed to other conditions, so vigilance and a low threshold for testing are needed. In lay terms, explain to the patient that you are arranging a blood test and possibly a scan because some persistent tummy symptoms, although usually harmless, occasionally point to an ovarian problem that is best caught early. Risk factors include increasing age, a family history of ovarian or breast cancer, and inherited gene mutations such as BRCA. Assessment: be alert in women, especially those 50 and over, with persistent or frequent symptoms — occurring more than twelve times a month — of abdominal distension or bloating, early satiety or loss of appetite, pelvic or abdominal pain, and increased urinary urgency or frequency. Also consider it with unexplained weight loss, fatigue, or change in bowel habit, and ask about family history. Examine the abdomen and pelvis for a mass or ascites. Red flags and the investigation pathway: in primary care, measure serum CA-125 first in women with the relevant symptoms; if CA-125 is 35 IU per millilitre or more, arrange an ultrasound of the abdomen and pelvis; if the ultrasound suggests cancer, refer on a suspected cancer pathway for assessment within two weeks. Refer directly if examination identifies ascites or a pelvic or abdominal mass that is not obviously uterine fibroids. A key teaching point: new symptoms suggestive of irritable bowel syndrome in a woman of 50 or over are uncommon, so investigate with CA-125 rather than diagnosing IBS for the first time at that age. Management: the primary-care role is recognising these vague but persistent symptoms, performing CA-125 and ultrasound appropriately, and referring without delay. Safety-netting is essential: in women whose initial tests are normal but whose symptoms persist, re-evaluate and consider repeat testing or referral, because ovarian cancer can present subtly and evolve over weeks to months.' },

  { id:'cks-breast-lump', cat:"Women's & sexual health", ic:'🎗️', dur:'5 min', title:'Breast lump & breast cancer', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for the breast lump and suspected breast cancer under NICE NG12. In lay terms, reassure the patient that most breast lumps turn out to be benign, but that any new discrete lump should always be checked, and that the breast clinic uses a combination of examination, a scan or mammogram, and sometimes a needle test to give a clear answer. Risk factors for breast cancer include increasing age, female sex, family history and BRCA mutations, early menarche and late menopause, nulliparity, obesity, alcohol, and prolonged combined HRT. Assessment: take a history of the lump — how and when it was noticed, any change with the menstrual cycle, and associated pain, skin or nipple change, or nipple discharge — and ask about risk factors and family history. Examine both breasts and the axillae systematically, noting the characteristics of any lump, skin tethering or dimpling, peau d\u2019orange, nipple inversion or change, and lymphadenopathy. Red flags and referral thresholds: refer on a suspected cancer pathway, for an appointment within two weeks, people aged 30 and over with an unexplained breast lump with or without pain, and people aged 50 and over with unilateral nipple changes such as discharge, retraction, or other concerning change; consider a suspected cancer referral for skin changes suggestive of breast cancer and for an unexplained axillary lump in those 30 and over; and consider a non-urgent referral in people under 30 with an unexplained breast lump. Management: refer according to the thresholds to the breast clinic, where triple assessment combines clinical examination, imaging with mammography or ultrasound, and biopsy where needed. Manage clearly benign findings such as cyclical breast pain or a confirmed benign lesion with reassurance and supportive measures, including a well-fitting supportive bra and simple analgesia for pain. Remember the routine breast-screening programme runs separately by age and does not replace assessment of a symptomatic lump. Safety-netting and referral: advise the person to return if a new lump or change develops, and arrange clear follow-up of results.' },

  { id:'cks-vaginal-discharge', cat:"Women's & sexual health", ic:'🔬', dur:'5 min', title:'Vaginal discharge & STIs', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for vaginal discharge and sexually transmitted infections. In lay terms, approach the topic without judgement, explain that some discharge is normal and changes through the cycle, and that where an infection is found it is common, treatable, and that testing and treating partners prevents reinfection and complications. Risk factors for STIs include a new or multiple partners, inconsistent condom use, and a previous STI. Assessment: take a sensitive sexual history — partners, practices, and protection — and ask about the discharge\u2019s colour, consistency, and odour, plus itch, pain, dysuria, and abnormal bleeding. Common non-sexually-transmitted causes are bacterial vaginosis, with a thin grey, fishy-smelling discharge, and vulvovaginal candidiasis, or thrush, with a thick, white, itchy discharge. Sexually transmitted causes include chlamydia, gonorrhoea, and trichomoniasis. Examine, where indicated, with a speculum to assess the discharge and cervix, and a bimanual to check for adnexal or cervical motion tenderness. Red flags: lower abdominal or pelvic pain with cervical motion tenderness, fever, or deep dyspareunia suggests pelvic inflammatory disease, which needs prompt treatment to protect fertility; and consider pregnancy-related and other causes of abnormal bleeding. Investigate with self-taken vulvovaginal swabs for chlamydia and gonorrhoea by nucleic acid amplification testing, a high vaginal swab where indicated, vaginal pH testing, and a full sexual-health screen including HIV and syphilis serology, ideally via sexual-health services. Drug management: treat bacterial vaginosis and trichomoniasis with metronidazole, and candidiasis with an antifungal such as clotrimazole or oral fluconazole; treat uncomplicated chlamydia with doxycycline, and gonorrhoea with ceftriaxone according to current guidance, ideally through sexual-health services because of resistance, testing of cure, and contact tracing; and treat pelvic inflammatory disease promptly with the recommended antibiotic combination, with a low threshold given the consequences of missed infection. Non-drug and public-health measures: arrange partner notification and treatment, offer a full screen, safer-sex advice, and contraception review. Safety-netting and referral: refer to sexual-health services for complex or recurrent infection, treatment failure, or where partner notification is needed.' },

  { id:'cks-subfertility', cat:"Women's & sexual health", ic:'🤰', dur:'5 min', title:'Subfertility', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for subfertility. Definition: failure to conceive after regular unprotected intercourse, conventionally for one year, prompting assessment of the couple. In lay terms, acknowledge the emotional weight of fertility problems, explain that difficulty conceiving is common and often treatable, and that assessing both partners together helps find the most helpful approach. Risk factors and considerations include the woman\u2019s age, which strongly affects fertility, previous pelvic infection or surgery, irregular or absent ovulation, low or high BMI, smoking, and male factors. Assessment: assess both partners together where possible. Investigate after one year of trying, but begin earlier, after six months, if the woman is 36 or over, or there is a known cause or risk factor such as previous pelvic infection, amenorrhoea, or cancer treatment. Ask the woman about menstrual regularity, previous pregnancies, pelvic infection or surgery, and cervical screening, and ask the man about previous fertility, illness, surgery, and lifestyle; cover smoking, alcohol, weight in both, and the frequency and timing of intercourse. Examine and check BMI. Investigate the woman with a mid-luteal progesterone, around seven days before the expected period, to confirm ovulation, plus chlamydia screening and confirming rubella immunity, and check thyroid function and prolactin if cycles are irregular. Investigate the man with a semen analysis, repeated if abnormal. Non-drug management is foundational and should be emphasised: give pre-conception advice to all — folic acid, smoking cessation, limiting alcohol, optimising weight, and advice on the timing and frequency of intercourse, aiming for every two to three days — as these modifiable factors affect both natural conception and treatment success. Management and referral: refer to fertility services according to local commissioning criteria for further investigation, such as assessment of tubal patency, and for treatments including ovulation induction, intrauterine insemination, and IVF; refer early where there is a known cause or the woman\u2019s age makes delay important. Safety-netting and support: support the couple emotionally, signpost to counselling and support organisations, and coordinate investigations efficiently to avoid delay.' },

]);
